<h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Prosecco's story begins in the rolling hills of Italy's Veneto region, where the <strong>Glera grape</strong> (formerly known as Prosecco) has been cultivated for over a millennium. Historical records from the Roman era reference a wine called "Pucino" from this area, though the first documented mention of "Prosecco" appears in 1593, named after the village of Prosecco near Trieste.</p>

<p>The grape's DNA heritage remained a mystery until recent genetic analysis revealed Glera to be an ancient variety with <strong>deep Italian roots</strong>, distinct from international varieties. This indigenous character explains its exceptional adaptation to the region's unique microclimate, where cool Alpine influences meet Mediterranean warmth across the Prosecco DOCG zones of Conegliano Valdobbiadene and Asolo Montello.</p>

<h3>The Sparkling Revolution</h3>

<p>While Glera produced still wines for centuries, the transformation to sparkling wine began in earnest during the 19th century. The development of the <strong>Charmat method</strong> (or Martinotti method) in the early 1900s proved perfectly suited to Glera's delicate, floral character, preserving the grape's fresh fruit aromatics better than traditional bottle fermentation.</p>

<p>Prosecco's global recognition accelerated dramatically after receiving <strong>DOCG status in 2009</strong> for the prestigious Conegliano Valdobbiadene zone. This classification, combined with strategic marketing and the rise of aperitivo culture, catapulted Prosecco from regional specialty to international phenomenon.</p>

<h3>Modern Global Expansion</h3>

<p>Today, <strong>Italy maintains strict geographic protection</strong> over the Prosecco name, but Glera cultivation has spread to Australia, Slovenia, and parts of South America. However, these international plantings cannot legally use the Prosecco designation, which remains exclusively tied to specific Italian territories.</p>

<p>Current Italian Prosecco production spans approximately <strong>25,000 hectares</strong>, with annual output exceeding 600 million bottles. This remarkable growth—from 150 million bottles in 2000 to current levels—reflects Prosecco's evolution from local treasure to global ambassador of Italian sparkling wine excellence, now outselling Champagne worldwide by volume.</p>

<h2>Grape Characteristics & Winemaking</h2>

<h3>Viticulture and Growing Requirements</h3>
<p>Glera, the primary grape behind Prosecco, thrives in the cool, mineral-rich soils of Veneto's hills. This vigorous variety requires careful canopy management to prevent overcropping, as excessive yields dilute the grape's naturally crisp acidity and delicate floral aromatics. The best producers limit yields to 13.5 tons per hectare in DOCG zones, well below Glera's natural productivity. Harvest typically occurs in early September, when the grapes achieve optimal balance between <strong>tartaric acidity levels of 7-9 g/L</strong> and sugar concentrations around 17-19° Brix. The grape's thin skin makes it susceptible to botrytis in humid conditions, requiring precise vineyard timing and selective harvesting.</p>

<h3>Fermentation and Winemaking Techniques</h3>
<p>The Charmat method defines quality Prosecco production, preserving Glera's inherent freshness and primary fruit characteristics. After gentle pressing and clarification, the base wine undergoes <strong>temperature-controlled fermentation at 16-18°C</strong> in stainless steel tanks to maintain clean, bright flavors. Secondary fermentation occurs in pressurized tanks with selected yeasts, typically lasting 30-40 days at controlled temperatures. Premium producers like Bisol and Nino Franco extend this period to 60-90 days, developing greater complexity and finer bubble integration. Malolactic fermentation is generally avoided to preserve Glera's characteristic tartness, though some producers in warmer sites may allow partial conversion for texture.</p>

<h3>Regional Expression and Terroir</h3>
<p>Prosecco's expression varies dramatically across its growing regions. <strong>Conegliano-Valdobbiadene DOCG</strong> produces the most structured wines, with steep, south-facing slopes contributing mineral tension and longevity. The area's sandstone and clay soils impart subtle salinity and enhanced aromatics. Asolo DOCG, with its volcanic soils, yields more powerful wines with greater aging potential. The broader Prosecco DOC region produces fruitier, more immediate styles, with the flatter terrain and alluvial soils emphasizing Glera's apple and pear characteristics over mineral complexity.</p>

<h3>Quality Indicators and Aging Potential</h3>
<p>Superior Prosecco displays <strong>persistent, fine bubbles</strong> that form a stable mousse, indicating proper riddling and disgorgement techniques. The best examples balance Glera's natural acidity (6.5-7.5 pH) with subtle yeast autolysis flavors developed during extended lees contact. While most Prosecco is designed for immediate consumption, premium Conegliano-Valdobbiadene examples can develop honeyed complexity and almond notes over 3-5 years. Vintage Proseccos from exceptional producers like Cartizze demonstrate remarkable evolution, gaining textural richness while maintaining their essential vivacity.</p>

<h2>What Does Prosecco Taste Like?</h2>

<p>Understanding Prosecco's tasting profile helps distinguish quality levels and styles, from crisp everyday bottles to complex vintage expressions that rival Champagne in sophistication.</p>

<h3>Appearance and Texture</h3>

<p>Quality Prosecco displays a pale straw to light golden color, with premium examples showing slightly deeper hues indicating extended lees contact. The mousse—those tiny bubbles—should be persistent and fine, creating a creamy texture rather than aggressive fizz. <strong>Cartizze and vintage Proseccos</strong> often exhibit smaller, longer-lasting bubbles that indicate superior secondary fermentation and bottle aging.</p>

<h3>Aromatic Complexity</h3>

<p>Prosecco's aromatics reveal its quality immediately. <strong>Primary aromas</strong> center on fresh orchard fruits—green apple, pear, and white peach—with floral notes of acacia and wisteria. The signature Glera grape contributes distinctive citrus zest and subtle tropical hints of pineapple.</p>

<p><strong>Secondary aromas</strong> from fermentation include fresh bread crust and subtle yeastiness in better examples, while <strong>tertiary development</strong> in aged Proseccos brings honeyed complexity, toasted almonds, and delicate mineral notes reflecting the region's limestone-rich soils.</p>

<h3>Palate Structure and Mouthfeel</h3>

<p>Premium Prosecco balances <strong>bright acidity</strong> (typically 6-7 g/L) with moderate alcohol (11-12% ABV), creating a refreshing, light-to-medium body. The texture should feel creamy rather than sharp, with fine bubbles providing gentle effervescence. Residual sugar varies from bone-dry Brut Nature to off-dry Extra Dry, the most traditional style.</p>

<h3>Flavor Development</h3>

<p>On the palate, expect layers of <strong>crisp apple and citrus</strong> leading to stone fruit flavors of white peach and apricot. Quality indicators include subtle mineral undertones—a chalky sensation reflecting Conegliano-Valdobbiadene's unique terroir—and delicate herbal notes of fresh mint or basil that distinguish superior examples.</p>

<h3>Finish and Quality Markers</h3>

<p>The finish separates good from exceptional Prosecco. Premium bottles offer a <strong>clean, persistent finish</strong> lasting 30-45 seconds, with lingering citrus zest and subtle almond notes. Mass-market versions often finish abruptly with residual sweetness masking the wine's natural character.</p>

<p><strong>Look for these quality markers:</strong> fine, persistent bubbles; balanced acidity without harsh sharpness; complex fruit layers rather than simple sweetness; and a mineral backbone that provides structure and food-pairing versatility.</p>

<h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Prosecco's remarkable journey from a humble northeastern Italian grape to a global sparkling wine phenomenon spans centuries of winemaking evolution. The variety's story begins with <strong>Glera</strong>, the grape's official name since 2009, which has thrived in the Veneto and Friuli regions for over a millennium.</p>

<h3>Ancient Roots and Geographic Origins</h3>

<p>Historical records trace Glera cultivation back to Roman times, when the grape flourished in the hills surrounding modern-day Conegliano and Valdobbiadene. The name "Prosecco" itself derives from the village of Prosecco near Trieste, where this aromatic variety was first documented in the 16th century. Italian ampelographers have confirmed through DNA analysis that Glera is indigenous to northeastern Italy, with genetic markers linking it specifically to the steep, mineral-rich soils of the Treviso province.</p>

<h3>The Charmat Method Revolution</h3>

<p>While Prosecco existed as a still wine for centuries, its transformation into the sparkling wine we know today occurred in the early 1900s. <strong>Federico Martinotti's invention of the tank fermentation method</strong> in 1895, later refined by Eugène Charmat, revolutionized Prosecco production. This technique preserved the grape's delicate floral aromatics—notes of green apple, white peach, and acacia blossom—that would be lost in traditional bottle fermentation.</p>

<h3>Modern Recognition and Global Expansion</h3>

<p>Prosecco's international breakthrough came in the 1960s when Italian producers began marketing it as an elegant, approachable alternative to Champagne. The establishment of <strong>DOCG status for Conegliano Valdobbiadene in 2009</strong> marked a pivotal moment, protecting the most prestigious production zones while distinguishing quality levels.</p>

<p>Today, Prosecco production has expanded beyond Italy's borders, with notable plantings in Australia's King Valley, Brazil's Serra Gaúcha, and Argentina's high-altitude regions. However, <strong>over 90% of global Prosecco still originates from Italy</strong>, where approximately 25,000 hectares of Glera vines produce more than 600 million bottles annually, making it one of the world's most successful sparkling wine categories.</p>

<h2>Grape Characteristics & Winemaking</h2>

<p>Glera, the primary grape behind Prosecco, is a vigorous, high-yielding variety that thrives in the cool, hillside vineyards of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia. This naturally productive grape requires careful canopy management to maintain quality, with yields legally capped at 13.5 tons per hectare in DOCG zones and 18 tons in DOC areas. The grape's thin skins and tight clusters make it susceptible to botrytis, demanding meticulous vineyard timing and selective harvesting, typically occurring in early to mid-September when acids remain crisp and sugars reach 9.5-10.5% potential alcohol.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Fermentation Philosophy</h3>

<p>Prosecco's signature freshness stems from the <strong>Charmat method</strong> (Metodo Martinotti), where secondary fermentation occurs in temperature-controlled stainless steel tanks rather than individual bottles. This technique preserves Glera's delicate floral aromatics—particularly white flowers, green apple, and citrus zest—while maintaining the grape's characteristic minerality. Primary fermentation typically occurs at 16-18°C over 15-20 days, followed by secondary fermentation at 12-14°C for 30-40 days. Malolactic fermentation is deliberately avoided to preserve the wine's vibrant acidity, which ranges from 6-7 g/L tartaric acid equivalent.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Regional Expression</h3>

<p>Glera's terroir sensitivity becomes evident across Prosecco's hierarchy. In the prestigious <strong>Conegliano Valdobbiadene DOCG</strong>, steep slopes with calcareous-clay soils and significant diurnal temperature variation produce wines with intense minerality, complex white fruit flavors, and remarkable longevity. The subzone of Cartizze, with its unique microclimate and ancient marine sediments, yields Proseccos of extraordinary finesse and concentration. In contrast, the broader Prosecco DOC encompasses flatter vineyard sites that produce approachable, fruit-forward wines with softer acidity and broader appeal.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Quality Markers</h3>

<p>Superior Proseccos exhibit several telltale characteristics: a persistent, fine mousse with pinpoint bubbles indicating proper secondary fermentation; aromatic complexity beyond simple fruit, including honey, almond blossom, and subtle herb notes; and a long, mineral-driven finish that reflects true terroir expression. The best examples show <strong>textural depth</strong> from extended lees contact and demonstrate the grape's ability to balance richness with refreshing acidity.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Evolution and Aging</h3>

<p>While designed for immediate consumption, quality Proseccos can evolve beautifully for 2-4 years. Base wines from top producers develop honeyed complexity, toasted bread notes, and deeper fruit concentration while maintaining their essential vivacity. Vintage-dated Proseccos from exceptional years, particularly from Conegliano Valdobbiadene's premier sites, can age gracefully for up to six years, developing nuanced tertiary aromas that showcase Glera's surprising aging potential.</p>

