<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically across quality levels, making proper cellaring knowledge essential for maximizing your investment. Unlike Champagne, most Prosecco is designed for immediate enjoyment, but premium expressions reward patient collectors.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 2-3 years of vintage, as the fresh citrus and green apple notes that define this style quickly fade. <strong>Prosecco DOCG Superiore</strong> from Valdobbiadene and Conegliano can develop beautifully for 5-7 years, with the mineral-driven terroir becoming more pronounced over time.</p>

<p><strong>Rive expressions</strong> and single-vineyard Proseccos showcase the greatest longevity, often improving for 8-10 years. Premium producers like Nino Franco's "Grave di Stecca" and Bisol's "Crede" develop honeyed complexity while maintaining their characteristic salinity.</p>

<h3>Evolution Profile</h3>

<p>Young Prosecco displays bright acidity with primary fruit flavors of pear, apple, and citrus zest. With proper aging, these wines develop <strong>secondary characteristics</strong>: brioche notes from extended lees contact, almond nuances, and enhanced mineral expression. The perlage becomes finer and more persistent, while the wine gains textural weight.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store Prosecco horizontally at 50-55°F with 70% humidity. Unlike still wines, sparkling wines are particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations, which can compromise the mousse. Avoid vibration and direct light, as UV exposure rapidly deteriorates the delicate aromatics.</p>

<h3>Quality Assessment</h3>

<p>Properly aged Prosecco maintains bright acidity with developing complexity. <strong>Warning signs include</strong>: flat bubbles indicating CO₂ loss, oxidative notes resembling bruised apples, or cork taint presenting as wet cardboard aromas. Premium bottles with natural cork closures generally age more gracefully than those with synthetic closures, which can allow gradual gas escape.</p>

